Did you know that happiness isn’t destined for everyone?
Those of us with trauma try to blend in with others, 
But in the end we know we will always be on the sidelines watching, not participating. 
When your stuff is too much for you to carry at times, there’s no way anyone would want to be a part of that. 
The realization that your meant to be alone isn’t the tough part. 
It’s accepting that’s hard, but you don’t have any other choice but to accept it. 
#trauma #childhoodtrauma #alone #acceptance #onthesidelines #nohappiness #destined #destiny #destinedtobealone #anxiety #anxietysucks #anxietylife

Every day has the ability to be beautiful. It’s what you make of it. While you may know me as a travel blogger, I’m on a new journey to better myself. I thought I could outrun my trauma that I’ve attempted to bury my entire life, but this week proved I can’t. I hurt someone because of that and that’s something I don’t ever want to do. So instead of sulking, I’m making changes. I decided to start ketamine therapy to help get me on course. Therapy has been great thus far, but I’m just so tired of carrying old things with me. I need to be done with all of that as it obviously affects others, not just me. So here’s to my new journey, which I’m dedicated to completing because I’m worthy. #travel #sunset #sunsetlovers #ketaminetherapy #personalgrowth #personalgoals #imworthy #selfimprovement

Even when it seems too tough to handle, you have to push yourself to get out there and keep trying. I certainly don’t feel like it, but I’m doing it. And it’s for me and no one else. What do you do when you’ve tried your hardest and it’s not enough? Keep trying harder. It’s not about making anyone happy. It’s about being happy bring me and that’s where this current travel journey is taking me. #travel #travelblogger #instatravel #selfimprovement #therapy #selfgrowth #selfgrowthjourney #pushyourself #pushthrough #pushyourlimits #ketaminetherapy

I Wandered Lonely as a Cloud 
BY WILLIAM WORDSWORTH

I wandered lonely as a cloud
That floats on high o'er vales and hills,
When all at once I saw a crowd,
A host, of golden daffodils;
Beside the lake, beneath the trees,
Fluttering and dancing in the breeze.
——————-
Every experience, interaction, and word spoken doesn’t affect only you as the speaker. I’ve decided I’m definitely not traveling anywhere for a bit and I’m going to work on me. My entire life I’ve hidden myself in a way to protect myself. I don’t want to live the way I have lived anymore. When I can still see my reactions based in trauma and that look in people’s faces that says you’re way too much, I don’t want to keep doing things the same way as they obviously haven’t worked. 

So this daffodil is like the small glimmer of hope I have left to move thru and past childhood trauma. It’s not sad - really. It’s not. If I said I had no hope, that would be really sad. But I do have some. I don’t know what’s in store for me, but if I made it this far, I’m certainly not giving up. #travel #travelblogger #daffodils #daffodil #daffodils🌼 #yellowflowers #yellow #therapy #childhoodtrauma #cbt #ketaminetherapy #optimism #williamwordsworth #poem #poetry #moveforward

What is she talking about now? Yes I’m usually talking about #travel but I hope you’ll pause a sec instead of scrolling by. 

How many times did you hurt in silence alone? How often did you think “I don’t want to burden others”? I freely admit that’s been me my entire life even though I didn’t think about it. I tried to be myself or authentic, but when you don’t know who you really are, it’s nearly impossible to be yourself with others. So that ends now for me. As difficult and uncomfortable it makes me, I’m going to be me from now on. That means it’s not all about beautiful sunsets or exotic locations. It’s also me when I’m having a bad day and I’m struggling. Why the change? For the first time in my life I actually saw the link, the chain, the thread that connects my past and all that goes with it and how it can and did hurt someone. Well I hurt someone, but it was because of my wanting to run from my past and knowing now I have no choice but to face my past head on. 

For a split second I felt what I guess I think “normal” feels like when I let myself just be and it felt good. So I guess my journey or travels for right now will be chasing feeling free. I’d love to hear your thoughts or suggestions, too. #adhd #adhdwomen #adhdsupport #childhoodtrauma #therapy #cbttherapy #ketaminetherapy #personalgrowth #personalgrowthjourney #travelblogger #selfimprovement #freedom #soulpain #soulhurts #traveldeeper #traveldiaries

Existing or living? Making decisions or letting life decide for us? It’s obvious I’m at a crossroads in my life. I’ve always been one to jump first and think later and it’s become apparent to me that has to stop. Several years ago I made a trip to the home of the Brontë family in England. My all time favorite book is “Wuthering Heights” by Emily Brontë and learned about a hike that one can take to see the inspiration for her book. I made the trip by myself but never thought about maybe taking someone with me out in the countryside alone. But some trips are meant to be taken alone. They may be scary or lonely or anxiety inducing, but they have to be done and that’s where I am. I’m asked what my plans are, what do I think I’ll do? I have no idea. I’m going to take however long I need and do what I need and what feels right for me and it’s not on any schedule. 

No need to feel sad for me as I don’t feel sad for myself. This is what needs to be done. I know it, my soul knows it, and I’m pretty sure anyone who’s ever interacted with me knows I need to do this. 

Have you ever had a soul changing experience? Let me know as I’m interested. #therapy #ketaminetherapy #selfcare #selflove #selfimprovement #travel #travelblogger #england #haworth #bronte #emilybronte #wutheringheights #literature #signpost #crossroads #soulpain #introspection #personalgrowth #personalgrowthjourney #keighley

Today’s a new day and it’s time to look forward. No matter how high up you are, how scared you might feel, and how much your body tells you to run, don’t. Feel it and know if you can get through this, you can get through anything. 

Scotland is one of my favorite places to visit and I was at Fort William taking pics after one of the most treacherous drives of my life. It was twisty turns roads and at some point you have to let go and trust the process. And that’s where I am right now in my life. I’m letting go and not trying to control anything including my emotions. I’ve done it my whole life and I can’t anymore. So embrace this new day and all the good things that can and will happen if you’re open to it. 

If you’re reading this and thinking this is about you, unless you were with me last week this is so not about you at all. I’ve seen how a real man acts who isn’t a narcissist and I’ll never ever settle for less again.

So many stairs to climb but what a reward at the end at Tian Tan Buddha in Hong Kong. Sometimes you can understand how big it is in theory, but only when you see it with your own eyes that you get the enormity of it all. 

It’s like life and our personal and spiritual growth. I never really thought about any of that I think, but I get why now. I was living still a hyper vigilant life just as I had as a child. Seven years ago I had a chance to participate in an ayahuasca ceremony. My life has changed so much since then. My biggest lesson learned then is one I’m relearning now and that’s to let go. I may appear controlling and I’m sure people who have known me could agree. But I now understand it as simply trying to keep myself safe. It’s just sad that I still unconsciously use the same coping techniques I did as a child so that has to change. But I’m so grateful that I’ve experience things in my life recently that have demotivated me to work on all of myself and not for any reason or anyone other than myself. 

So take it one step at a time and know that like me you are strong, smart, and capable of anything you put your mind to. 

If you’re reading this and thinking this is about you, unless you were with me last week this is so not about you at all. I’ve seen how a real man acts who isn’t a narcissist and I’ll never ever settle for less again.

I’m often asked where is my favorite place to visit and that’s a hard one to answer. All the places I’ve visited have made a mark on me. One that really did was Easter Island. Seeing the Moai was more than I ever expected. I had no idea just how many exist, more than 1,000. And when you see them, you can look at them as merely statues or realize that they were carved to represent individuals. Some were carved with a pukao, or red scoria stone, to represent the long hair the deceased had. High ranking men often wore their hair tied in a bun on their heads. So my red hair actually isn’t unusual as Pakomio had red hair, blue eyes, and light white skin. In Polynesian culture, reddish hair has  been seen as a sign of descent from high-ranking ancestors and a mark of rulership. Maybe that’s why I liked it there so much. Maybe I was there in a previous life. 

But when you look at each statue, to me they were more than statues because they had personalities. Not everyone will see it or even care. But I saw it and felt it and ultimately, that’s all that matters. 

That’s true of everything in life. I have spent my entire life people pleasing and avoiding conflict, but not understanding how all of my actions (subconscious vs conscious; intentional vs unintentional) still can and do affect others and often, if not always, produces unintended outcomes. I’m extremely focused on removing these obstacles from my life so it will allow me to be happy. And not happy because of someone but solely for me, because of me. 

Life is too short not to embrace all opportunities, even when it seems harder then I can handle. If the Moai each can weigh up to 14 tons and no one was complaining about that, I think I can learn some valuable life lessons and continue to better myself. 

Here’s to a good week filled with possibilities for self improvement and of course, travel. ✈️🗿

Travel has always been important to me and I feel so fortunate to travel to places I’d only dreamt of seeing someday. When I traveled back to Colombia and made my way along the Amazon, I felt so lucky. Where else was I going to see pink dolphins or some of the world’s largest lily pads? 

On this particular day, the sky opened up and it was pouring. We were trying to wait out the rain as we were still traveling by boat. Then some children started playing futbol and then some of the men in my group joined in for a wet, messy, but laughter filled game. 

The lesson is clear: There’s joy in everything if we look for it. It’s easy to get annoyed by the everyday mundane and annoying things in life. If you do, you’ll miss out on all the laughter that could have otherwise occupied your stress filled day. 

So what have we got to lose? Absolutely nothing!

Was out and about today and stopped in at the Enchanted Forest Reiki Center. I’ve been meaning to visit for over a year, but I wasn’t too far away today so it seemed destined. Look at this gorgeous Hamsa Hand 🪬 with Evil Eye 🧿. I recently read not to keep a broken or damaged Evil Eye. I broke a Evil Eye keychain and kept the pieces so I guess that was a no-no. 🧿 So when I saw this one, I knew it was going home with me. 

If you’re not familiar with the Hamsa Hand or the Evil Eye, this briefly covers it: 

“The Hamsa Hand is a universal sign of protection, power and strength that dates back to ancient Mesopotamia. Known as the Hand of Fatima in Islam and Hand of Miriam in Judaism, it's believed to protect against against the evil eye and and all negative energies.”

I’m all about protection and positivity so in addition to my permanent Hamsa Hand tattoo I have, I enjoy learning about other cultures and religions with regard to protection from evil. I also have an Icelandic rune for protection tattoo as well as a necklace, and a St. Benedict’s medal that I wear primarily for ghost hunting or any other time I feel it’s needed. 

Are you someone who will roll your eyes when you hear Evil Eye or protection? Or do you feel it as well? Besides being a beautiful little piece of art, the added bonus of protection makes it a must have in my book. 🧿🪬

Thailand is a country I know I will always return to because it has so much to offer. When I visited Bangkok and went to Wat Pho and other temples, it felt familiar and comforting to me. But we are usually too  preoccupied with our lives to pay attention. But guess what? I’m paying attention now. So I’m making myself a priority as well as travel. It’s all about just being happy.

Happy Sunday! Thought I’d try something new so here goes. 

SUNDAYS IN VEGAS:

1. Started the day off with a reiki session with Selise at Enchanted Forest Reiki Center. Definitely helped with how I’ve been feeling, but looks like I was spot on with regard to my sacral chakra. 
2. Finally made my way over to Ronald’s Donuts because they have vegan donuts of course. I got the maple bar and an old fashioned. Intended to only eat 1/3 of the maple bar, but it was so light and tender that yeah — I ate the whole thing because it was so good. 🍩
3. Went to the brand new Grocery Outlet  on Blue Diamond. It’s small, but they had Daiya cheese for $1.99 and Tattooed Chef quesadillas or burritos for $0.99 and a big ass candle for $5.99 (shelf display said $4.99 but I’ll deal with that next time). It reminded me a little of Aldi. When I lived in Los Angeles, I kept meaning to go into a Grocery Outlet, but never did. I’m definitely returning to this one. 
4. Got a Mango Monsoon at Tropical Smoothie Cafe. I realize how much the Philippines has spoiled me because I want a mango only smoothie. This had mango, pineapple, papaya, guava, passion fruit & coconut. Again, I wanted just mango, especially as I don’t really like papaya. But you can’t take just papaya out. Long story. Trust me. But it’s still a good smoothie. I just wanted a mango smoothie. Anyone know where in Vegas I can get a vegan mango only smoothie? 
5. PLATONIC on AppleTv+: watched episode six and I was hysterical watching @sethrogen and Alan argue, especially this: 
Will: You will die before me. 
You have osteoporosis. 
I love the writing on this show. Hopefully, the writer’s and actors strike may be over soon.🤞🤞🤞
6. FILTERS ARE FUNNY: I wanted to use this pic because the filter made my eyes weird so now I look like a robot. Well, the truth was going to get out eventually. 😄

There are some things that I like to see  where I live that immediately give me comfort. Water is my all time favorite and living in Vegas has taken some getting used to as I’ve enjoyed always being near a body of water. In Boston, I  had an amazing view of Boston Harbor. My other favorite is mountains. I grew up with views of Mount Adam and Eve in New York so not sure if that’s why I like seeing mountains. But mountains definitely look different on the West coast. I am always in awe of the mountains that surround Las Vegas. Perhaps it’s because it’s always so sunny here and then you have these  incredibly blue skies, the palm trees, and the relatively flat terrain that turns into various types of hillsides and mountains. But the beauty of those mountains never elude me. 

What is a must have for where you live? Is it water, mountains, beaches, or something else? Could you live without it? Why or why not?

This is one of the many beautiful statues at Tirta Empul Temple in Bali, Indonesia. I’ve been thinking a lot about Bali this week. “Tirta Empul,” which means “Holy Spring” in Balinese, is a famous Hindu Balinese water temple that was created  all the way back in 962 A.D. 

The purification process in the water may seem unusual and complicated to foreigners, but people do this not only on special days, like a full moon, but every day. That’s why it was a little cringey for me watch tourists using it as a pool to do laps. 😳 

You can’t take pics while you’re in the water, which is why I don’t have a pic, but the grounds there definitely deserve a walk around. Especially their koi pond. I’ve never seen so many giant koi in one place. 

Why do I love Bali? There’s a sense of calm there and so much joy and love. The Balinese people are so friendly and welcoming, too. Can’t wait to return soon again!

So excited to be planning a trip! I’ve been craving the ocean so I can dip my toes in and get some ocean energy and I just went ahead and did it. Now living in Las Vegas and going to California May not seem like a big deal to most, but remember I’m an East coast girl so California and the Pacific Ocean are still somewhat new to me. Yes, I lived in LA for a year, but that was during Covid and I never found my way to the ocean. 

Ocean water is so therapeutic for me. I feel calmer and more centered so instead of dreaming about it, I’m doing something about it. It’s a short trip but I’m really excited about going. Can’t wait to sit and people watch and also have the chance to watch the sun rise and set over the water. I’m going to grab a beach towel and park my butt on the sand for as long as I possibly can. 

Where do you go to recharge?

With all that’s going on in the world, it can feel overwhelming. I think anytime innocent people, especially children, are killed, our first reaction is revenge and justice. But we all know how that turns out. This isn’t about whether or not you follow the news or politics either. 

I’m trying very hard every single day to be a better person. Working on myself daily isn’t my idea of fun, but in the past month I’ve felt considerably calmer and my heart is full of love for myself and others. Amazing how you can, if you choose to, redirect your pain and angst into love and non-judgment toward the world. Can you imagine what it would feel like if everyone tried that? 

We are all connected and in the end, we are all in this together. You never know what anyone is going through or experiencing and kindness and compassion are not just important, but necessary. 

So I’m still learning how to “sail my ship” by loving myself first daily. When you haven’t done that your entire life and you suddenly realize it, that’s a good enough reason to change.

Bright colors always grab my attention and while walking through Little India in Singapore was a definite feast for my eyes. You’ll see tons of vendors near the temples selling items and I wanted to buy them all. 

Between the flowers, shops, art, and food, I was definitely overstimulated but in a good way. When you’re visiting somewhere new and you don’t have much time, it’s best to have a plan. I’ve learned now that having ADHD, I like a plan, but I don’t want to be over scheduled either. I will research what’s available to see and do, but I’m not going to even attempt to do everything on a list. 

For me, talking with locals or doing things in the moment is far more meaningful than hitting every tourist trap at a destination. 

If you have ADHD, do you have any travel tips to share?

Is it weird that I miss sweater weather? Growing up in NY and living most of my adult life in Boston, I hated cold weather and snow. What I mostly disliked was the gray and gloomy sky. 

But there’s something very weird about it being almost November in Las Vegas and I’m still wearing short sleeves. Ok I admit I wear them year round and still haven’t pulled out the requisite gloves, hat, scarves, boots, etc. like I see so many wearing here by December. 

I do miss seeing the leaves change color in New England and what a variety of colors autumn brings to the landscape. 

Snow I’m still not in love with but I love how beautiful Iceland is any time of year, but especially in winter. That and it’s only a 4 1/2 hour flight from Boston. It’s a great getaway, especially if you like nature, food and drink (think Brennivin or Opal), and my favorite, history. 

This pic was taken at Thingvellir National Park in iceland. Thingvellir translates to Assembly Plains and the General Assembly convened from 930 until 1798. This is where the legislative assembly met and where laws were written to avoid conflicts. 

As if that wasn’t cool in itself, this is the only place in the world where you can actually see where the North American tectonic plate and the Eurasian tectonic plate meet. 

I guess I need to grab some sweaters and a coat and head to iceland. ❄️❄️❄️

Since I’m now living in the desert in Las Vegas, I’m reminded of my visit to Egypt and when I got to see the pyramids in person (and the Sphinx, too!) 

I’m not sure what I was expecting, but I guess I shouldn’t have been surprised by so many tourists. I also had the chance to walk down and inside one of the pyramids. My childlike wonder and excitement was at an all time high. What would I see? Well, it was an empty concrete room with an air conditioner. 😳 Left feeling a little deflated, but at least I got to see it and experience it for myself. 

Sometimes things don’t go as planned. So what do you do? You can feel disappointed or you can learn something from the experience, right? It’s what you learn along the way and not just at the destination. 

For anyone traveling to Egypt, advance warning about the Sphinx. The tourist area around it has a very slippery surface. I tripped and nearly fell and saw others having the same issue. Someone in our group actually fell and broke her arm so wear shoes that grip. Sounds silly but I’m telling you it was so slippery! 

Not sure when or where my next trip will be but I’m definitely looking for another adventure.

When I was driving from New York to California in 2020, I planned my trip with stops along the way, like to the Bonneville Salt Flats in Utah. It was like nothing I’d ever seen before and beautiful in its own raw and natural way. 

As I think about trips I’ve taken and places I’ve been, it also makes me think about many things, including people I’ve met along the way. It’s taken me my entire life to get to a stunning realization about myself. So much like the salt flats, I’m going to be raw and natural. I’ve not only disliked myself my whole life, I’ve had zero love for myself. 

If you’ve ever met me in person, been an acquaintance or friend or more, or family, I’m sorry. There’s no way I could’ve been kind or decent to anyone without being able to love myself first. 

While I post pics of my travels, I’ve never let my followers get to know me and that’s why. Because I didn’t even know myself. These past two months have been life changing for me and I don’t say that lightly. I am putting in the work to learn who I am and why I am the way I am. It’s hard work and it’s exhausting, but it’s so necessary. I’ve learned that all I want is to be: be happy, free, and at peace. 

I suspect there’s going to be a lot of changes in the next year with what I do here online and with me and I welcome any and all to join me on this new adventure in my life. While it may not be straight up travel anymore, I’m looking forward to what the Universe has in store for me.

For those vegans among us like myself, sushi can be well… boring. You can only have a cucumber or avocado roll so many times right? I was at Whole Foods at Town Square grabbing a few things and I like to visit the sushi area to torture myself a bit. I was in for a surprise when I saw they now carry Kiki’s Sushi plant based sushi. I grabbed the crunchy “tuna roll” and while it’s about $3 more than plain veggie sushi, I thought I’d give it a go. 

While I’ve been vegan for about six years, I’ve started eating vegetarian since I was 17. I first stopped eating pork, then chicken, then shrimp. You see I don’t mention beef as I never liked it and I only really ate chicken in the form of nuggets and shrimp as in fried shrimp. Took me awhile to figure out it was the crunchy coating I liked. But I digress. I did have sushi a few times I believe, but honestly can’t recall what I had or if I liked it. 

So this was a true test as if it tasted too “fishy,” I’d never get it again. The verdict? DELISH! Like i could easily eat this and the other kinds of Kikka Sushi all the time. Total yumminess!

Why you should go with the flow and not over plan: Went back to the beach and well, couldn’t see anything. The marine cover was thick and although it was 70°, it was cold. I decided against sitting on the beach and decided to grab a drink and wait it out. 

Truth be told, I haven’t had a drink in about two months and after reading about how cannabis affects dopamine levels to which I’m already deficient because of my ADHD, I stopped that as well. One margarita and I totally feel it. The humidity has my hair all poofy and while I longed for an afternoon just sitting on the sand, I’m not going to stress about it. No need to get upset and I’m learning to go with it. Just means I need to plan another trip here soon. 

Why? I’m working very hard on letting go. I had a life changing experience about two months ago that forced me to look at myself and see that although I’ve made changes in my life, I have a long way to go. Letting go of old ways of thinking and behavior can be difficult, even painful, but the end result of loving yourself and being happy is what I’m after. 

So letting go with a margarita while in California really isn’t a bad thing. Ask anyone who’s known me and that’s a big change from where I’ve been previously. 

And no, it’s not the tequila talking I promise. 😉 But I know working on me is what I need to do right now. I have no big plans for travel at the moment and not being in any kind of relationship or dating is perfect for me right now. I’m getting to know me so much better, turning off all that crazy negative self talk, and finding ways to help others. Dare I say I’m happy? You bet! 😁 And I’m not even dwelling on anything at the moment. Just being me. Happy Friday everyone!

I’ve never been a big Thanksgiving fan because I’ve not eaten meat since I was a teen. But this year I realized I’ve missed the point entirely. Yes, people live for the copious amounts of food they’ll consume that day, but Thanksgiving isn’t really about the food. It’s about giving thanks and this year I have so much for which to be thankful. My health, my son, my home, my friends, and more. I’ve also made a lot of changes this year because I was given the opportunity to look at how my actions truly affect others. That was a hard, but life changing lesson to learn. The more I work on myself, the happier and more at peace I become. Took me a long time to get here and I know I’ll never be done, but as rough as this year was, it was a good year nonetheless. 

So I decided to make a vegan Thanksgiving feast for myself. All homemade but for the Whole Foods vegan roast. I made biscuits, mashed potatoes, creamed spinach, and orange walnut cranberry sauce. Delicious but definitely way more than I’m used to eating now. I still haven’t learned to cook for one so leftovers ahead! 😁

I’m also learning to have gratitude daily so Thanksgiving is just one day of saying thanks. Let’s do it every day! I hope everyone enjoyed their Thanksgiving and was able to tell the people in their lives how important they are to them. 
.

.
.

Have you ever walked a labyrinth? I have previously and wanted to do it again. Think of it as a walking meditation. It’s not a maze and is unicursal, which means there’s only one way in and one way out. Labyrinths date back as far as 4,000 years ago and can be found in various cultures around the world. 

You basically walk with an intention to receive whatever it is you’re supposed to receive. It can be used as a prayer tool or for mindfulness. There’s no right or wrong way to walk a labyrinth and it’s not a competition between you and anyone else. When you get to the center, you can pause and reflect before resuming. But the best part is that since this is for you, you decide when and how you do it. 

For anyone like me who has difficulty with meditation for any variety of reasons (for me it’s #ADHD), a walking meditation allows my body to focus on the walking while my brain lets go. It helped me release some of what I’ve been holding onto this week and receive what I needed, which is that I am never truly alone. 

There’s a worldwide labyrinth locator here: https://labyrinthlocator.com

Let me know if you’ve tried one and where it was or if you’re thinking about trying one.

Gulfoss Falls, Iceland. Powerfall, majestic, and reminds me I do like snow when I haven’t seen it in awhile. 

Gulfoss, which translates to “Golden Falls” in English is one of the attractions you will visit if you do the Golden Circle route. It is the largest waterfall by volume in Europe. There’s something magical seeing it in the winter under snow, but any time of year is a great time to visit Iceland. 

Ok who is planning a trip to Iceland and taking me with them? 🇮🇸❄️🏔️🗻

location.city_name: St Michaels Cave, Rock Of Gibralter

social_posts.post_text:
Inside St. Michael’s Cave, Gibraltar. I’m forever amazed by nature’s handiwork like the stalactites and stalagmites located here. This is the most famous of the more than 150 caves located inside the Rock of Gibraltar and evidence shows that prehistoric man visited as far back as 40,000 BC. Today, approximately 1,000,000 people visit each year. 

Gibraltar is an interesting place to visit with monkeys (Barbary macaque), history, shopping, and more. If you fly there, the The Gibraltar airport is the only commercial airport in the world that has a highway passing across its runway.

I was just talking to a friend about how much I love the windows in Amsterdam. Between the tall, skinny buildings and tall, skinny windows, I love most of the places where I’ve stayed were flooded with light and had great views. 

In case you didn’t know, the reason for the tall, skinny buildings dates back to the 17th century when the city calculated taxes based on the width of a building. So instead of going wide, many decided to go narrow and tall. If you are a keen observer, you’ll probably notice the hooks near the top. They’re there to help those heavy items to the upper floors. You can see the one on this building at the very top center with the hook tucked inside its little wooden case. And those shutters - they’re everything! 

Looking forward to a return trip to Amsterdam hopefully soon although big plans are shaping up for me for 2024. I’m looking at going abroad for a few months and living the digital nomad life. Now if I could just rent out my Vegas place for a few months, it would be perfect. 😊

I’ve always had a thing for planes. I’ll stop and just watch a plane fly overhead even though I’ve seen so many in my lifetime. One of the last places I lived in Boston was directly across from Boston Logan International airport. I used to love watching the line of planes coming in at night. 

In Las Vegas I found the best places to plane watch is of all places, the Whole Foods parking lot at Town Square. Located about ten minutes south of the Strip on S Las Vegas Blvd. it is a shopping area with tons of shops, restaurants, and activities. Every time I go I think about taking pics or video but never do. 

Today was different as it was early (by Vegas standards) and chilly (again by Las Vegas standards) and there was hardly anyone out at about 10:30 am. But there I was watching the planes fly by. They flew out higher than normal, perhaps because of the cloud cover or weather conditions but normally I can see the belly of the plane and they feel so close flying right over the parking lot. Think Maho Beach in St. Maarten, but different. 😊✈️🛫🛩️
